<subSubSection pageNumber="335" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="335">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="335">Note: 
<taxonomicName authority="L." authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1759" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Astragalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sesamoides">Astragalus sesamoides L.</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="335">Amoen. Acad.</emphasis>
4: 489. 1759) was regarded by Stearn (in Geck &amp; Pressler, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="335">Festschr. Claus Nissen</emphasis>
: 632. 1974) as an orthographic variant of 
<taxonomicName authority="L." authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Astragalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sesameus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="335">A. sesameus</emphasis>
L.
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="335">Sp. Pl.</emphasis>
2: 759. 1753). This seems perfectly plausible, because the phrase name used by Magnol (
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="335">Bot. Monsp.</emphasis>
: 194. 1676), &quot;Ornithopodio affinis hirsuta stella legiminosa&quot;, cited (only slightly altered) from Bauhin (
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="335">Pinax</emphasis>
: 350. 1623), was treated as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Astragalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sesameus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="335">A. sesameus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Linnaeus in 1753. Moreover, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1759" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Astragalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sesamoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="335">A. sesamoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
never appears again in later works, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Astragalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sesameus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="335">A. sesameus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does (see Turland &amp; Jarvis in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="335">Taxon</emphasis>
46: 464. 1997).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
